# Multi-Agent Hard Rules

When two or more agents / sessions touch the same repository at the same time, the default failure mode is silent: one agent stashes, reverts, or overwrites another agent's uncommitted work, and nobody notices until production breaks. The rules below each prevent a specific class of data loss.

> **Boundary with `multi-worktree.mdc`**: that file covers the **pre-flight scan + claim mechanism** (4 mandatory scans, HANDOFF.md format, conflict resolution priority). This file covers the **operational hard rules** that apply once parallel work is in flight (worktree isolation, magnet files, git constraints, pre-merge checklist). Read both.

## 0. Pre-flight Self-check

Before touching any file:

1. Run `git status`. If the working tree has many untracked or modified files you did not create:
   - Those may belong to another agent that has not committed yet.
   - **Forbidden**: `git stash`, `git clean -fd`, `git checkout .`, `git reset --hard` against those files.
   - **Forbidden**: drive-by refactors or "cleanup" of those files.
   - Read `.cursor/agents-active.md`. If another agent is registered as working on overlapping files, **stop and report to the user**.
2. Confirm the current branch:
   - On `main` / `master` / a protected branch → create a new branch before any edit.
   - On a feature branch → verify it is yours, not another agent's.
3. Register yourself in `.cursor/agents-active.md` (one line, see Appendix A). Remove your line when the task ends, success or failure.

## 1. Physical Isolation (the single most important rule)

Parallel agents **must** use independent git worktrees on independent branches. Never let two agents share a single working directory.

```bash
# Main checkout at ~/repos/<project>
git worktree add ../<project>-agent-A feat/agent-A-<topic>
git worktree add ../<project>-agent-B feat/agent-B-<topic>
```

Why:

- File-system writes are physically separated; one agent cannot stomp another agent's unsaved buffer.
- Per-worktree build caches (`node_modules`, `target`, `__pycache__`, IDE indexes) stay independent.
- Each agent has its own `git status`, so the pre-flight check stays meaningful.

If your tooling provides isolated worktree subagents (e.g. Cursor's `best-of-n-runner`), prefer that over manual setup.

## 2. Split Tasks Along Module Boundaries, Not Feature Boundaries

Identify the repo's natural module axes before assigning parallel tasks. Hard rule: **if two tasks must edit the same file, run them serially**. Parallel assignment is only allowed across **disjoint** file sets.

The concrete axis table (per-service / per-resource / per-feature folder) belongs in the consuming repo's `project/` binding — see Appendix B for the placeholder list.

## 3. Magnet Files (shared files, never write in parallel)

Some files are touched by nearly every feature. Concurrent writes here will conflict and one side will be lost. Maintain an explicit list per repository (Appendix B). Typical magnet files:

- i18n / translation files
- shared protocol or schema definitions
- API client / RPC binding entry points
- routing / navigation / sidebar registry
- top-level App / root component
- dependency manifests (`package.json`, `go.mod`, `Cargo.toml`, `requirements.txt`, `pyproject.toml`)
- build config (`webpack`, `vite`, `tsconfig`, `cargo` workspace)
- lockfiles (`package-lock.json`, `yarn.lock`, `pnpm-lock.yaml`, `go.sum`, `Cargo.lock`)

Protocol:

1. **Front-load the changes.** Before launching parallel agents, make a single commit that adds every shared field, key, route, or dependency the upcoming parallel work will need. Land it on the base branch.
2. **Read-only during parallel phase.** Each agent treats magnet files as read-only.
3. **Serial fallback.** If a magnet-file edit cannot be avoided, serialize: one designated agent owns the change end-to-end.

## 4. Git Behavior Constraints

1. **Rebase-only.** Before merging back into the base branch, run `git rebase <base>`. Resolve conflicts inside your own branch. **Forbidden**: merge commits into the shared base.
2. **Small commits, push immediately.** Push each chunk to your own remote branch — protects against crashes, makes progress observable, keeps conflict boundaries clean.
3. **Stay on your branch.**
   - Forbidden: `git checkout` to another agent's branch or to the base branch.
   - Forbidden: `git push --force` to any branch you do not own.
   - Forbidden: `git push --force-with-lease` to base / protected branches.
   - Forbidden: `git reset --hard` to a remote position behind local (discards commits another agent may have pushed).
4. **Do not rewrite shared history.** `git rebase -i`, `git commit --amend`, `git filter-branch` may only target commits you created in this session **and** that exist only on your own branch.
5. **No cross-task stash juggling.** Any `git stash push` must be `git stash pop`-ed within the same task context. Never carry stashes across tasks or across agents.
6. **Never delete a branch you do not own.** Including local pruning.

## 5. Test Gate (last line of defense)

Every agent runs the full automated test suite before pushing. Multi-agent context adds: **before merging, rebase onto the latest base and re-run the full suite**. This catches "I broke another agent's contract" regressions.

The exact test commands per language stack belong in the consuming repo's `project/` binding, not here.

Cross-feature tests (integration, contract, end-to-end) are **not optional** even if your local change feels isolated — they are the fastest way to detect inter-agent contract breakage.

## 6. Merge Order and Cadence

1. Merge the **infrastructure PR first** (the magnet-file front-load from §3). All feature branches must rebase onto it before continuing.
2. Merge feature branches **smallest diff first**. Minimizes rebase pain for branches landing later.
3. After **every** merge to base, run the full test suite on base before merging the next branch.
4. If two feature branches discover an unavoidable conflict at merge time, **stop the parallel pipeline**. Resolve by serializing: pick one branch to land first, rebase the other on top, re-test.

## 7. Coordination Table (lightweight but mandatory)

The repository contains an `.cursor/agents-active.md` file (template in Appendix A). It is the live registry of who is working on what.

- **Read it before starting any task.** Overlapping target files → stop and report to the user.
- **Register yourself before editing any file.**
- **Remove your entry when the task ends**, success or failure.
- The coordination table is itself a magnet file — update with a single read-then-write atomic edit.

## 8. Mandatory Cleanup Before Launching Parallel Agents

If `git status` on the base branch is not clean (lots of untracked files, scattered modifications), **do not launch parallel agents yet**. First:

1. Group existing changes into logical commits by feature subset.
2. Land them on the base branch, or on a dedicated `wip/staging` branch with a clear owner.
3. Confirm `git status` is clean.
4. Only then create worktrees for parallel agents.

Skipping this guarantees that the first thing parallel agents do is stash or overwrite each other's pre-existing work.

## 9. Pre-merge Checklist

- [ ] Work performed in an independent worktree on an independent branch
- [ ] No magnet files modified, or if so, change was coordinated with all other active agents
- [ ] `git rebase <base>` ran cleanly; no merge commits introduced into the shared base
- [ ] Full test suite passes on the rebased branch
- [ ] `git status` inside the worktree is clean; no other agent's uncommitted files swept into this commit
- [ ] Agent's entry in `.cursor/agents-active.md` removed
- [ ] No `git push --force` to any branch the agent does not own
- [ ] No history rewriting on shared commits

